{"parse":{"title":"Nightingale ward","pageid":8345608,"revid":775185078,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>Nightingale ward</b> is a type of <a href=\"/wiki/Hospital\" title=\"Hospital\">hospital</a> ward, which contains one large room without subdivisions for <a href=\"/wiki/Patient\" title=\"Patient\">patient</a> occupancy.  It may have side rooms for utilities and perhaps one or two side rooms, that can be used for patient occupancy when patient isolation or patient privacy is important.  Nightingale wards contain about 24 to 34 beds usually arranged along the sides of the ward. Modern wards tend to separate patients into bays, each usually containing 4 to 6 beds. Observation of the patients by the nursing staff tends to be easier in a Nightingale ward than in bays. In one study, 75% of patients preferred being nursed in a bay rather than in a Nightingale ward.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The Nightingale ward was named after the pioneer of modern nursing, <a href=\"/wiki/Florence_Nightingale\" title=\"Florence Nightingale\">Florence Nightingale</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nightingale_ward&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">David, Deborah (28 May 2011). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nursingtimes.net/roles/nurse-managers/we-should-not-dismiss-the-value-of-nightingale-wards/5030393.article\">\"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">'</span>We should not dismiss the value of Nightingale wards<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">'</span>\"</a>. <i>Nursing Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">13 April</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Nursing+Times&amp;rft.atitle=%27We+should+not+dismiss+the+value+of+Nightingale+wards%27&amp;rft.date=2011-05-28&amp;rft.aulast=David&amp;rft.aufirst=Deborah&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nursingtimes.net%2Froles%2Fnurse-managers%2Fwe-should-not-dismiss-the-value-of-nightingale-wards%2F5030393.article&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANightingale+ward\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Pattison, HM; Robertson, CE (April 1996). \"The effect of ward design on the well-being of post-operative patients\". <i>Journal of advanced nursing</i>. <b>23</b> (4): 820\u20136. <a href=\"/wiki/PubMed_Identifier\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"PubMed Identifier\">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8675902\">8675902</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+advanced+nursing&amp;rft.atitle=The+effect+of+ward+design+on+the+well-being+of+post-operative+patients.&amp;rft.volume=23&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=820-6&amp;rft.date=1996-04&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F8675902&amp;rft.aulast=Pattison&amp;rft.aufirst=HM&amp;rft.au=Robertson%2C+CE&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ANightingale+ward\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160